The capital of France is Paris a major European city known for its art fashion culture and landmarks like the Eiffel Tower and the 12th-century Notre-Dame cathedral. Paris is also renowned for its cafe culture and the Louvre Museum which houses the Mona Lisa among other masterpieces

Water boils at 100 degrees Celsius at standard atmospheric pressure which is one atmosphere. This temperature is equivalent to 212 degrees Fahrenheit. The boiling point can change depending on the atmospheric pressure for example it is lower at higher altitudes due to decreased pressure

The Great Wall of China stretches over 21 196 kilometers or about 13 171 miles. It was built over several dynasties mainly to protect against invasions and raids by nomadic groups from the Eurasian Steppe. The wall is not a single continuous structure but a series of walls and fortifications

The human body has 206 bones. These bones are categorized into two major groups: the axial skeleton which includes the bones of the skull vertebral column and rib cage and the appendicular skeleton which includes the bones of the limbs and girdles that attach them to the axial skeleton

Python is a popular programming language known for its readability and simplicity. It supports multiple programming paradigms including procedural object-oriented and functional programming. Python is widely used in web development data analysis artificial intelligence scientific computing and more

The tallest mountain in the world is Mount Everest which stands at 8 848 meters or 29 029 feet above sea level. It is part of the Himalaya range in Asia and straddles the border between Nepal and the Tibet Autonomous Region of China. Mount Everest attracts many climbers including highly experienced mountaineers as well as capable climbers willing to hire professional guides

The Mona Lisa is a portrait painting by the Italian Renaissance artist Leonardo da Vinci. It is considered an archetypal masterpiece of the Italian Renaissance and has been described as the most famous most visited most talked about and most parodied work of art in the world. The painting is thought to depict Lisa Gherardini a woman from Florence

The speed of light in a vacuum is approximately 299 792 kilometers per second or about 186 282 miles per second. This constant is denoted by the letter c and is a fundamental constant in physics. The speed of light is crucial in many areas of physics particularly in the theory of relativity where it establishes a limit on the speed at which information can travel

William Shakespeare wrote Romeo and Juliet one of his most famous plays which tells the story of two young star-crossed lovers whose deaths ultimately reconcile their feuding families. It was among Shakespeare's most popular plays during his lifetime and along with Hamlet is one of his most frequently performed plays. Today the characters of Romeo and Juliet are regarded as archetypal young lovers

The chemical symbol for gold is Au which comes from the Latin word 'aurum' meaning gold. Gold is a precious metal that has been used for coinage jewelry and other arts throughout recorded history. It is highly valued for its rarity resistance to corrosion and unique color. Gold is also an excellent conductor of electricity and is used in electronics and dentistry

The currency of Japan is the yen symbolized by Â¥ and abbreviated as JPY. The yen was introduced by the Meiji government in 1871 to replace the complex monetary system of the Edo period. It is currently the third most traded currency in the foreign exchange market after the United States dollar and the euro. The yen is often used as a reserve currency after the US dollar the euro and the British pound

Mars is often called the Red Planet because of its reddish appearance which is due to iron oxide or rust on its surface. Mars is the fourth planet from the Sun and is a terrestrial planet with a thin atmosphere composed primarily of carbon dioxide. It has surface features both of Earth-like characteristics such as valleys deserts and polar ice caps and of more alien features such as the largest volcano in the Solar System Olympus Mons

The Pacific Ocean is the largest and deepest of Earth's oceanic divisions. It extends from the Arctic Ocean in the north to the Southern Ocean in the south and is bounded by Asia and Australia in the west and the Americas in the east. The Mariana Trench located in the western Pacific is the deepest part of the world's oceans reaching a maximum known depth of about 11 034 meters or 36 201 feet

Guacamole is a popular dip spread or salad made from avocados. Its origins are traced back to the Aztecs in Mexico. Traditional ingredients include mashed ripe avocados sea salt lime juice onions cilantro tomatoes and chili peppers. Guacamole is often served with tortilla chips or used as a condiment in various Mexican dishes

Albert Einstein developed the theory of relativity which revolutionized our understanding of space time and gravity. His most famous equation E=mc^2 states that energy is equal to mass times the speed of light squared. This theory has had profound implications for physics and has led to numerous technological advancements

The Great Barrier Reef located in the Coral Sea off the coast of Queensland Australia is the world's largest coral reef system. It is composed of over 2 900 individual reefs and 900 islands stretching over 2 300 kilometers or 1 400 miles. The reef is home to a diverse array of marine life and is a popular destination for tourism diving and research

H2O is the chemical formula for water. It consists of two hydrogen atoms covalently bonded to one oxygen atom. Water is essential for all known forms of life and covers about 71% of Earth's surface. It is found in oceans rivers lakes and the atmosphere. Water is also a major component of the human body and is involved in numerous biological processes

The Eiffel Tower is located in Paris France. It was constructed from 1887 to 1889 as the entrance arch to the 1889 World's Fair. The tower is named after the engineer Gustave Eiffel whose company designed and built the structure. It is one of the most recognizable structures in the world and a global cultural icon of France

World War II ended in 1945 following the unconditional surrender of the Axis powers. The war began in 1939 and involved most of the world's nations including all the great powers which eventually formed two opposing military alliances the Allies and the Axis. It was the deadliest conflict in human history marked by significant events including the Holocaust and the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki

The Nile is the longest river in the world flowing northward through northeastern Africa for about 6 650 kilometers or 4 130 miles. It is an international river as its drainage basin covers eleven countries. The Nile has two major tributaries the White Nile and the Blue Nile. It has historically been considered the longest river but in recent years some studies suggest the Amazon River might be slightly longer

The primary colors are red blue and yellow. These colors are the building blocks for all other colors and cannot be created by mixing other colors. When combined in various ways these primary colors can produce a wide spectrum of colors used in art and design

Mount Fuji located on Honshu Island is the highest mountain in Japan standing at 3 776 meters or 12 389 feet. An active stratovolcano that last erupted in 1707 Mount Fuji is a well-known symbol of Japan and is frequently depicted in art and photographs. It is also a popular destination for climbers and tourists

Diamond is the hardest natural substance on Earth with a hardness of 10 on the Mohs scale. It is a crystalline form of carbon with its atoms arranged in a crystal lattice structure. Diamonds are used in jewelry due to their brilliance and durability and in industrial applications such as cutting and grinding tools due to their hardness

Venus is the hottest planet in our solar system with surface temperatures averaging around 467 degrees Celsius or 872 degrees Fahrenheit. This extreme heat is caused by a runaway greenhouse effect where its thick atmosphere composed mainly of carbon dioxide traps heat. Venus is often called Earth's sister planet due to its similar size and composition

Neil Armstrong was the first man to walk on the moon on July 20 1969 during the Apollo 11 mission. His famous words as he stepped onto the lunar surface were That's one small step for man one giant leap for mankind. The mission marked a significant achievement in human space exploration

Mandarin Chinese is the most spoken language in the world with over a billion native speakers. It is the official language of China and Taiwan and one of the four official languages of Singapore. Mandarin is also one of the six official languages of the United Nations

The heart pumps blood throughout the body through a network of arteries veins and capillaries. The right side of the heart receives deoxygenated blood from the body and pumps it to the lungs for oxygenation. The left side of the heart receives oxygenated blood from the lungs and pumps it to the rest of the body. This circulation is essential for delivering oxygen and nutrients to tissues and removing waste products

The blue whale is the largest mammal and indeed the largest animal ever known to have existed. It can reach lengths of up to 30 meters or 98 feet and weights of 170 tonnes or more. Blue whales are found in oceans worldwide and are known for their deep loud calls which can be heard over long distances

The Amazon Rainforest also known as Amazonia is located in South America and spans across nine countries including Brazil Peru and Colombia. It is the largest tropical rainforest in the world covering approximately 5.5 million square kilometers or 2.1 million square miles. The Amazon Rainforest is incredibly biodiverse home to millions of species of plants animals and insects many of which are not found anywhere else in the world
